item.title: The Truth About The Ancient Egyptian 'Board Game Of Death'
item.description: This simple game of chance began as a casual activity at the time of its invention, but Egyptologists suspect that around 2300 BCE, the game took on a religious significance with practitioners believing it offered them a conduit to the dead. Think of it like a competitive Ouija board. Contemporaneous Egyptian codices reference the game as a reflection of the soul's movement through Duat, the Egyptian plane of the dead. Archaeological evidence appears to confirm this acquired meaning, as boards from about 1300 BCE onward replaced the basic squares of the early senet boards with hieroglyphic birds associated with the Egyptian soul.

item.title: Translating to IPC: All This for 3%?
item.description: Contrary to popular belief, increasing IPC is difficult. Attempt to ensure that each execution port is fed every cycle requires having wide decoders, large out-of-order queues, fast caches, and the right execution port configuration. It might sound easy to pile it all on, however both physics and economics get in the way: the chip still has to be thermally efficient and it has to make money for the company. Every generational design update will go for what is called the ‚Äòlow-hanging fruit‚Äô: the identified changes that give the most gain for the smallest effort.

item.title: What is gypsum lath?
item.description: Answer Gypsum lath (rock lath) is made out of gypsum plaster sandwiched between two sheets of absorbent paper, and it is used in the construction of walls.
